headline: Lululemon Shares Drop After Apparel Maker Says Tariffs Will Hurt Profits
summary: Shares of Lululemon Athletica fell 15% in after-hours trading Thursday after the maker of yoga pants cut its fiscal-year outlook, saying it expected higher tariffs and the end of the de minimis exemption to dent its profits by $240 million this fiscal year.  Lululemon, based in Canada, makes products in China, Vietnam, Cambodia, Sri Lanka, Indonesia and Bangladesh.  Chief Executive Calvin McDonald said the company was disappointed with the results in its U.S. business as well as Lululemon’s product execution.

headline: Lululemon stock sinks after Q3 outlook disappoints
summary: Shares of Lululemon Athletica (LULU) fell sharply in after-hours trading. The retailer reported second quarter earnings of $3.10 per share, which was better than the $2.87 that was expected. Net revenue was $2.53 billion which was close to the expected $2.54 billion. For Q3, the company sees earnings of $2.18 to $2.23 per share. The estimate was $2.90. Net revenue is projected to be in a range of $2.47 billion to $2.50 billion. Wall Street was expecting $2.56 billion. The company also lowered its full-year earnings and revenue guidance. CFRA Analyst Zachary Warring says it was a "pretty bad quarter overall," but points to international growth as a potential bright spot. headline: Lululemon (NASDAQ:LULU) Misses Q2 Sales Expectations, Stock Drops 12.9%
summary: Athletic apparel retailer Lululemon (NASDAQ:LULU) missed Wall Street’s revenue expectations in Q2 CY2025, but sales rose 6.5% year on year to $2.53 billion. headline: Lululemon cuts forecasts, blames tariffs and product issues
summary: (Reuters) -Lululemon Athletica slashed its annual profit forecast for the second quarter in a row, blaming weak U.S. business and product issues, as well as tariff costs.  Shares of the yogawear maker, which also cut its annual sales forecast, fell about 15% after the closing bell.  The company's attempts to boost sales and fight competition with weekly product launches have failed to spark a wave of buying from shoppers, as it steps into the holiday-focused second half of the year.
